JD Eaton Richards was 29 when he died, and is commemorated at Loos.

He was 'killed while gallantly leading the machine gunners of whom he was in charge' at the Battle of Loos on 25th September 1915.  He was 'admired [...] so much for his pluck, bravery, and many good qualities'.
By January 1915, he had secured his transfer to the Royal Sussex Regt and became a Machine Gun Officer. It was this role that he maintained until September 1915.

I found him to be based at Le Harve, away from enemy lines, and by November 14, he was already questioning his role. Not uncommon for REPS officers, JD Eaton-Richards wrote this in his diary: https://t.co/Oxi3ifiAC4
JD Eaton-Richards was one of the first to join up when war was declared, and was in France as a young 2nd Lt by 11th September 1914.

Despite doing well in his Indian Civil Service exams, he applied for and sat exams for the Open Competition, Assistant Surveyor, Class II GPO, with his first posting to Scotland. On the 1911 census he's listed as 'Assistant Surveyor Second Class, GPO, Cheltenham'.

Julian David Eaton Richards - son of a clergyman, born May 1886 in Yorks, educated at Sherborne School, then Wadham College, Oxford (and a firm candidate for #historicalhottie ) His background was not unusual for GPO surveyors either. https://t.co/66GR6dT6lm
So where does JD Eaton-Richards fit into this, given he's commemorated on the Royal Sussex Memorial?

The REPS were 4000 men strong by 1918 (half the size of the RE Signals Service), and were pedemoninatley GPO employees from across the four nations, united by what they knew at home - mail, communications, and logistics. https://t.co/Wg0TXcemK5

The REPS are too easily forgotten, especially at this time of year, and what I found was a body of men bound by duty to their nation in two distinct ways. They were already serving the country - the GPO was an army in its own right, uniform, rank, service. Then they went to war.

I came across JD Eaton-Richards when researching the General Post Office surveyors - the regional managers of the 1880-1918 GPO if you will. That path took me down my favourite burrow - the men of the Royal Engineers Postal Section (REPS).

Final tweet - MP competitors have some balls. They jump an unknown horse round a 1m20 course after a 10/15 min warm up & it may have already ditched their rival.

In comparison the Olympic eventers show jumped their life long horses around 1m22-1m28 course for the team medals
I’ve seen worse at local shows, riding schools, and even out affiliated. It’s not acceptable across the board, don’t only call it out once every four years because you saw it on the tele.
Please don’t put the international standard rose tinted glasses on - the actual show jumping was just as bad, if not worse this morning, no one’s slagging that off?

Guess my point is it’s not easy viewing, Saint Boy will no doubt need schooling, and some competitors need a bloody good talking to. However until MP comes under FEI rules, or the riding is taken seriously the standard will never improve.

Some of those riders may never have ridden a horse that naps/stops/rears.
Without experiencing it, you would not know how to respond - napping and rearing can be terrifying. 

I draw the line as at a coach punching a horse though.

Did the riders behave well? Under FEI rules some would be yellow carded, others banned. 

What must be remembered is that MP athletes are not riders, very few will ride as their main sport, instead picking it up once a month to practice.

Horses can react to the smallest/biggest/weirdest of things. One rider’s advanced horse is another person’s beginner horse. 

They can pick that up a mile off and behave in 101 different ways in response. The fact that ‘resistance’ is defined in the MP rules says it all.

Was that horse suitable? For the job of jumping a 1m20 course, no doubt it was. They were all good horses.

Was that horse suitable for a bonkers arena with more than one unknown rider in the space of 90mins of questionable ability - perhaps not.

The biggest change modern pentathlon needs is for the riding to come under FEI rules. That said under the UIPM rules, there are clauses for behaviour, whip use, and unsportsmanlike behaviour.

There may still be fall out, but will be lost in the uproar of a 30 second video.

So @BritEquestrian @JamesHickBHS @BritishHorse please please do the right thing, work together and convince the Govt it is safe (and necessary) to continue.

Final tweet - the benefits it provides physically and mentally outweigh so much. The relationship between rider, horse, (and coach in lessons), the focus, the distraction, the exercise, the fresh air. The safest and best place I’ve been since May is my own centre.

Don’t @ me re safety/risk vs pressure on the NHS. You reduce risk ie no jumping. In three years of equine admin/management roles, I can count on one hand the number of times I called for an ambulance.
Equine welfare already has an overstocked versus wanted problem. Closing centres could mean even more horses surplus to requirements, and what to do with them?

Businesses still have utility rates to pay (want to guess the water bill of a medium sized yard?); services such as vet/farrier still needed/paying; insurance costs; membership schemes; staff costs - can’t just ignore horses for a month.
Huge number of self employed throughout equine industry . Without yard work or clients they will have little if any income.

Also worst possible time to leave horses who are used to work stood in fields/boxes. It’s wet and dank, hay prices are through the roof, feed prices will increase due to poor harvest, ground will be trashed a lot quicker. Yards in all forms need income. Livery alone won’t cut it.
It’s outdoors (or in freezing cold ‘indoors’, never found a warm one), you don’t get anywhere near your coach, you wear gloves, and tack is cleaned between clients.
Absolutely no reason why one on one/private lessons cannot continue. Business issues aside of privates rarely make money, it’s better to have some income than none at all.
Not to mention equestrian sports! Another closure will mean the end for a huge portion of the industry. https://t.co/GgxyX70DMJ

While the APOC was originally known as the PO Rifles, the histories of the two c.1914 - 1918 are different, & must be remembered as such.
By 1914, the APOC had become the Royal Engineers Postal Section, and exclusively recruited from the GPO, unlike the PO Rifles.
While the 24th Middlesex became 8th (City of London) Batt, London Regt, (PO Rifles) they did not continue to be the Army Post Office Corps.
In Egypt, Sudan & the Second Boer War, they were acting as the Army Post Office Corps, under the title of the 24th Middlesex. https://t.co/qHN3CF3kjC
